import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// Written from the project README and the CVPR-format writeup in tex/.
// If the paper gets a public link (arXiv, PDF on the site), add it to `meta`
// as a fourth entry.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="Audio Recommendation — case study"
	description="A music recommender that learns from what a track sounds like and says, aligning audio and lyric embeddings instead of relying on metadata or collaborative filtering."
	eyebrow="Case study — 2025"
	heading="Audio Recommendation"
	lede="Most recommenders learn from what other people played next. This one only listens — aligning audio and lyric embeddings so similarity comes from the track itself."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'Python · PyTorch · transformers · librosa' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'Research project · CVPR format' },
		{ label: 'With', value: 'Hailey Davio, UMBC' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista/AudioRecomendation', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista/AudioRecomendation' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The problem</h2>
		<p>
			Collaborative filtering recommends what people like you played next, which works well
			until a track has no audience yet — and works badly for anyone whose taste doesn't sit
			neatly inside an existing cluster. Genre tags have the opposite failure: they're stable,
			but far too coarse to separate two records that share a label and nothing else.
		</p>
		<p>
			Both are proxies. The question was whether the signal could come from the recording
			itself instead — its texture and its words — with no metadata and no other listeners in
			the loop.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The pipeline</h2>
		<ol class="cs__steps">
			<li>
				<strong>Spectrograms.</strong> MP3s are loaded with <code>librosa</code> and rendered
				as log-frequency spectrograms — audio as an image, which is what lets a vision-style
				transformer read it.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Audio embedding.</strong> A pretrained Audio Spectrogram Transformer
				(<code>MIT/ast-finetuned-audioset-10-10-0.4593</code>) encodes each spectrogram into
				768 dimensions.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Alignment.</strong> For tracks with lyrics, a CLIP text encoder produces a
				512-dim lyric embedding. The AST vector is projected down to 512 and pulled toward
				its lyric pair with a symmetric InfoNCE loss (learned temperature, AdamW).
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Reduction.</strong> The aligned space is reduced to three principal
				components, which is small enough to plot and inspect by eye.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Recommendation.</strong> A user profile is a handful of songs; a
				recommendation is a nearest neighbour by Euclidean distance in that PCA space.
			</li>
		</ol>
		<p>
			Training used the FMA large subset — 106,574 tracks across 16,341 artists and 161 genres
			— with each track trimmed to thirty seconds.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Evaluating without users</h2>
		<p>
			There's no clean way to pull real listening histories off a streaming platform, so
			there was no ground truth to score against. Evaluation fell back to cluster geometry:
			build small hand-curated libraries, then compare intra-cluster distance (how tight one
			person's taste sits) against inter-cluster distance (how far two people's tastes sit
			apart). If the embedding carries taste at all, the first should be reliably smaller than
			the second.
		</p>
		<p>
			It's a sanity check rather than a benchmark, and the writeup is explicit about that.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Where it breaks</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Lyrical sentiment and musical tone disagree constantly — an upbeat arrangement over
				bleak words gives the contrastive objective two honest but opposing targets.
			</li>
			<li>
				Instrumental tracks have no text side by definition, and no centralised lyrics
				dataset covered the full corpus anyway.
			</li>
			<li>
				FFmpeg's codec library wasn't present on the HPC partition used for training and had
				to be built by hand and put on <code>PATH</code> before anything would decode.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			The interesting failure wasn't technical. Aligning two modalities assumes they're
			describing the same thing, and music is the case where that assumption is weakest —
			the gap between what a song sounds like and what it says is often the point of the song.
			A stronger version of this would model that disagreement rather than train it away.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
